observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the: 
(a) MDRRMO and members of the emergency response team (i) attend trainings to gain knowledge and understanding, awareness and skills for prevention, mitigation, preparedness, response, rehabilitation and recovery; and (ii) maintain the minimum standards of power tools/heavy equipment at the minimum as required by the disaster preparedness minimum standards volume 2 of the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council;
(b) management (i) explain the deficiencies noted on the procurement of Elf Truck; 
(ii) make sure that specifications for the procurement of goods shall be based on relevant characteristics and/or performance requirements and that reference to brand names shall not be allowed; (iii) submit the documentary deficiencies for the transactions stated above; and (iv) observe the existing rules and regulations on procurements; and
(c) Municipal Accountant and the Acting GSO install an effective internal control in the recording, management and issuance of supplies and materials in accordance with the above-mentioned guidelines.

We recommended that the management:
(a) explain the deviations made on the prescribed rules and guidelines for the BGCM under LBC No. 125 and strictly comply with the requirements provided for all grant and funds received; 
(b) submit the documentary deficiencies for the transactions stated above and henceforth observe the existing guidelines on emergency procurements including the preparation and submission of documents for auditing purposes; 
(c) ensure that all procurement during the year are within the approved Annual Procurement Plan and in accordance with Republic Act 9184; and 
(d) return the unutilized fund to the National Treasury.

We recommended that the:
end-user of the goods needed to combat COVID-19 (i) conduct initial scanning of the prevailing prices of drugs, medicines, and medical devices; and (ii) apply DOH issuances on suggested retail price granted to certain goods prior to the preparation of the purchase request;
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) comply with the mandatory documentation of procurement proceedings and ensure that resolutions recommending award thereafter are reviewed to avoid conflicting details thereon;
Municipal Accountant (i) coordinate with the BAC in the submission of the required documents to the Office of the Auditor for further evaluation; (ii) ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment to substantiate the regularity of claims; and, (iii) prepare a note to disclosure in the financial statements on the status of the receipt and issuance of in-kind donation; and,
Management install an effective and efficient internal control over the receipt and issuance of in-kind donations in conformity with COA Circular Nos. 2014-002 and 2020-009.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment not later than January 31 of each year;
Acting GSO to (i) maintain Property Cards for each type of property in coordination with the Office of the Municipal Accountant; (ii) issue the corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) to fix the accountability of the end-user over the property; and (iii) maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card;
Representative of any office receiving any property from any source to secure all turnover documents or deed of donation from the donor and furnish the Accounting and GSO Office a copy for proper recognition of the same in the books of accounts, simultaneous with the fixing of accountability therefor;
Municipal Engineering Office to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Acting GSO the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects and, on the basis of which, the Municipal Accountant to record the same in the books of accounts;
Municipal Treasurer (or General Services Officer) to take immediate action to ensure that registration and titling of the subject parcel of land in the name of the Municipality is undertaken; and
Municipal Accountant to (i) set up and maintain a lapsing schedule for the PPE items to ensure the accuracy of the periodic depreciation charges for each PPE; (ii) prepare and maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC); (iii) recognize donated properties in the books of accounts; and (iv) prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to capitalize several capital expenditures, and recognize the depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation related to such assets, if applicable.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer to (i) ensure that all identified projects will be implemented without further delay; and (ii) continue to monitor and supervise the implementation of projects under the development fund;
direct the Local Development Council to specify the projects, programs and activities under the Development fund and stop the practice of lump-sum budgeting and inclusion of generic items in the Annual Investment Plan and Annual Budget, otherwise secure prior authority from the Local Sanggunian;
ensure that any change in the annual budget is supported with valid authority and documentation pursuant to Section 321 of R.A. 7160 and Section 454(2)(b) of its IRR; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) review the recognition of transactions for certain capital expenditures funded by the Development Fund and draw correcting entries therefor; and (ii) reconcile her records with the Municipal Engineer, re-evaluate the nature and intent of expenditures in order to properly recognize all improvements made on various properties in the books of accounts, and adjust the cost of PPE when applicable.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Accounting Office, Treasurer’s Office and Inventory Committee, as the case may be, to:
(a) conduct complete physical count of all properties and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment; 
(b) prepare and maintain subsidiary ledger cards for each group of PPE; 
(c) keep property cards for each class off PPE;
(d) set up a spreadsheet application or lapsing schedule for the PPE items to facilitate the computation for the periodic depreciation for each PPE item; and 
(e) facilitate confirmation with the Land Registration Authority (LRA) and seek technical assistance, if necessary, for the titling of all lots in the name of the Municipality of Masantol.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Accounting Office, Treasurer Office and Inventory Committee, as the case may be:

 (a) to conduct complete physical count of all properties and submit the Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment; 

(b) prepare and maintain property cards  for each category of assets starting with current year’s acquisition; 

(c) facilitate confirmation with the Land Registration Authority (LRA) and seek technical assistance, if necessary, to be able to have the remaining 11 lots titled in the name of the Municipality of Masantol.

We recommended that the:

 Local Chief Executive as head of the MDC, work out for the completion of the composition of the MDRRMC in accordance with the RA 10121;

Members of the MDRRMC institute the functional organization of the ICS, the required training and resource management which include the personnel, teams, equipment, and other facilities available during emergencies, as a perfect tool in responding to all types of hazards most particularly in an on-scene emergency situations and calamities such as flooding;

 Management, thru the MDRRM Office, prioritize the preparation and completion of a 10-Year DRRM Plan that will serve as the general strategy in addressing disaster risk reduction and management as prescribed in RA 10121; and

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer install an effective internal control in the recording, maintenance and distribution of relief items and disaster response equipment in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal HRMO to:

 require the physical presence of personnel and the submission of their duly verified/accepted Daily Time Records (DTRs) bi-monthly and monthly Accomplishment Report before payment of their salaries;

prepare the Statement of Duties and Responsibilities detailing the work assignment and functions of every hired JO to prevent duplication of tasks between them and the regular/permanent employees;

evaluate timely the performance of personnel and review the necessity of their     employment; and

maintain individual personnel file of pertinent records and documents at the HRM Office upon hiring such as PDS, resume, government issued photo-bearing ID,  job order contract and the statement of duties and responsibilities for each job.

In addition, we encouraged the HRMO to closely coordinate with the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer on its commitment in DILG Memorandum Circular 2014-83 regarding the membership of JOs with the SSS.

We commended the Local School Board for complying with DepEd-DBM and DILG JC No. 01. s. 2017 in providing education facilities, but we also recommended:

 continue its practice in appropriating funds more on the construction /repair of classrooms to help the National Government address the shortage of classrooms;

along with the Budget Officer, prepare the SEF Budget using the prescribed format under  DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 01, s. 2017;

 thru the Municipal Accountant, take appropriate action to recover the ₱3,938.00 overpayment from the supplier;

Municipal Accountant to check the completeness/correctness of the amount to be paid before payment of the transaction, and

 as far as feasible, seek the help of the provincial government and other national agencies for additional funds for the construction of additional classrooms for schools identified with high priority and with available site.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
reconstitute its GAD Executive Committee to abide with its mandated composition and include other key officials that can contribute to the committee;
institutionalize a working and functional GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) or a similar GAD mechanism to catalyse and accelerate gender mainstreaming;
encourage and direct the GFPS Committee and Technical Working Group to perform its mandated tasks; and
cause the establishment of GAD database.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and the Municipal HRMO:
require the physical presence of personnel and the submission of their duly verified/accepted Daily Time Records (DTRs) bi-monthly and monthly Accomplishment Report before payment of their salaries;
prepare the Statement of Duties and Responsibilities detailing the work assignment and functions of every hired JO to prevent duplication of tasks between them and the regular/permanent employees;
evaluate timely the performance of personnel and review the necessity of their employment; and
maintain individual personnel file of pertinent records and documents at the HRM Office upon hiring such as PDS, resume, government issued photo-bearing ID,  job order contract and the statement of duties and responsibilities for each job.

We recommended that the management:

(a) discontinue the grant of cash advances to elected officials other than for travelling expenses;

(b) prohibit the issuance of additional cash advances to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made; 

(c) grant cash advance only to those permanently appointed and bonded officials; and 

(d) improve compliance to the laws, rules and regulations in the granting and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

institutionalize a working and functional GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) or a similar GAD mechanism to catalyze and accelerate gender mainstreaming within the Province;

encourage and direct the GFPS Committee and Technical Working Group to perform its mandated tasks;

cause the establishment of GAD Database; and

require the GAD focal person to prepare its accomplishment report based on the approved GPB.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal HRMO to:
require the physical presence of personnel and the submission of their duly verified/accepted Daily Time Records (DTRs) bi-monthly and monthly Accomplishment Report before payment of their salaries;
prepare the Statement of Duties and Responsibilities detailing the work assignment and functions of every hired JO to prevent duplication of tasks between them and the regular/permanent employees;
evaluate timely the performance of personnel and review the necessity of their     employment; and
maintain individual personnel file of pertinent records and documents at the HRM Office upon hiring such as PDS, resume, government issued photo-bearing ID,  job order contract and the statement of duties and responsibilities for each job.
In addition, we encouraged the HRMO to closely coordinate with the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer on its commitment in DILG Memorandum Circular 2014-83 regarding the membership of JOs with the SSS.

We recommended that Members of the Provincial Local School Board:

prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization, particularly the guidelines set under DepEd/DBM/DILG Joint Circular No. 1, S 2017, on the preparation of the SEF budget and its utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;

request for inputs from the DepEd office/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;

maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives and monitor the implementation of the PPAs.

We also recommended that Local Chief Executive instruct the member of BAC and its Secretariat to (i) subject all procurements to public bidding unless the conditions are present for the use of shopping and small value procurement as alternative mode of procurement; and (ii) comply strictly with Section 54.1 of the RIRR of RA No. 9184 on the prohibition of splitting of contract.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage the active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;

through the Acting MENRO, comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and by collecting only those garbage that are properly segregated;

take appropriate action to expedite the relocation of the informal settlers near the MRF;

provide necessary support in enjoining the remaining 25 barangays to establish their own MRF;

recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003; and require the MSWM Board to finalize the 10-Year SWMP.

We recommended that the Accounting Office, Treasurer Office and Inventory Committee, as the case may be:

 (a) mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items and in the event that documents needed to obtain costing of PPE is no longer feasible, consider the fair value thereof as point of reference pursuant to PPSAS 17;

(b) prepare and maintain property cards  for each category of assets;

(c) strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and actual inventory results;

(d) facilitate confirmation with the Land Registration Authority (LRA) and seek technical assistance, if necessary, to be able to get the lots titled in the name of the Municipality of Masantol.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and the MENRO:

(a) seek approval of the plan from the National Solid Waste Management Commission; 

(b) coordinate efforts and implement the five basic environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment required under R.A. No. 9003; 

(c) involve closely the Barangay officials and civic leaders in the strict implementation on the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign at the household level on the ordinances issued by the Municipality; and 

(d) seek the help of private companies/organizations in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of waste and “no littering” policies.

We recommended that the Members of the Local School Board:

(a) prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;

(b) request for inputs from the DepEd official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;

(c) maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary; and

(d) submit above-cited lacking documents and henceforth, comply with the required documentation for similar transactions.

We recommended that  Members of the Provincial Local School Board:
prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization, particularly the guidelines set under DepEd/DBM/DILG Joint Circular No. 1, S 2017, on the preparation of the SEF budget and its utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;
request for inputs from the DepEd office/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;
